['Kyle is one of the most successful entrepreneurs in the tech world taking on one of the most difficult and exciting problems in AI (building autonomous vehicles) and testing in one of the most challenging environments in the United States (San Francisco). Plus, he went to MIT, so it was great to have this conversation with him back on campus. Hope you enjoy as well.', "it'll be interesting to see what happens when these cars have 100,000, or 200,000 miles on them. All cars after 200,000 start to break down no matter how well they are built. And when that happens it ain't much of a concern when your car blows a gasket, or a belt. However, it concerns the hell out of me when an autonomous vehicle is poorly maintained and then runs down some poor bicyclist on their way home from work. I think this kyle guy should be focusing on a more efficient electric car.", 'Kyle must be back on the show. He is an amazing person.', "GM hasn't made 9 million vehicles since 2017. It's been all downhill since then.", 'I have free ideas ...always üòè', 'I had to go see about a startup...Son of a bitch. Stole my line.', 'The approach that all self-driving companies are taking to address the crux of the problem - achieving (a competent) human level performance which is demonstrated by human ability to generalize - is unlikely to be achieved by the "edge case by edge case" grinding that the guest and others in the industry are doing. The artificial intelligence targeted for the task of self driving needs to achieve the generality required in this task (not AGI but generality within the narrow domain of driving) to be able to replace humans at scale. The early success of achieving human level detection (this is still somewhat debatable as seen by some silly errors made by the machine) on image datasets has created a high expectation that any task involving human intelligence (beyond sensing i.e perception and planning in this case) may be matched or superseded by machine intelligence but this has proven to be much harder as seen by companies like Waymo (and now Cruise and others) that have been grinding at the problem for many years and yet not able to claim human level performance. If you have to keep tuning and engineering the system for more and more novel cases, you are not really demonstrating true generality. It is also not clear as you tune for more and more cases, are you degrading prior cases (sort of like the game of whac-a-mole) or are you truly building up intelligence? Even if you are building up intelligence, it may just be more fitting by increasing complexity of machine learning models rather than true generalizing on very novel scenarios (outside of the training distribution). There must be some intrinsic physics type of model that is happening in the human cognition that makes a human never make silly mistakes or get totally baffled on novelty in driving, and we see no evidence of this yet in the machines. In that sense, we may be hitting a limit that is higher but fundamentally not too different than the old school AI if/then/else case enumerations to solve this problem.

A human driver that has achieved a certain level of competence in driving can drive quite well in any new geography (e.g another country) or environment where s/he has never driven before and then can also learn quickly in the new environment to be as agile as in the known environments. Until the machines are able to demonstrate this level of performance, they will remain inferior even as they may show statistically better performance due to avoiding fatalities happening due to incompetent human drivers (drunk, distracted etc driving).', 'Great interview.   I love hearing from tech people who have helped launch successful businesses.  The combination of business and tech skills seems rare to me (but I may be wrong).  An idea---provide startup financing in exchange for the right to film all aspects of a start up from day zero‚Äîthen gather the successful start-ups and create an instructional reality show,  a class, or maybe just one feature length movie, ‚ÄúHow They Really Did It‚Äù, or some better title.

I liked Kyle‚Äôs list of elements of a start-up for him:  something useful for others, something that you can scale up to increase that usefulness, something with a challenging core tech problem to solve, and something you would be willing to commit 10 years of your life to.  And then be willing to do all the less interesting tasks that have to be done to succeed at anything.  

I was moved by the background of the interview.  Lex works in the AV field (I think) and is a professor at MIT, and Kyle is someone who dropped out of MIT to help create and sell two businesses for $1B, the second of which was in the AV world.  I liked that Lex and Kyle delved into those choices without judgment or envy.  We all have choices to make that involve money, fame, family, personal satisfaction of discovery, and other aspects of life.   Not always easy.

A different note:  I think it would be great to bring together successful business people, scientists, economists, and futurists and brainstorm how to have the science fiction world of the future without the social and economic dystopia. 

As to AV, what will happen to the world when people no longer have to drive?  They can live much farther out from the city, sleeping in their cars, or can work remotely from their AV and drive all over the planet.  Will it be as Thomas Wolfe wrote, ‚Äúyou can never go home again,‚Äù or as the song goes, ‚Äúwe‚Äôre always home, but we‚Äôre always gone, living in a mobile home.‚Äù

Thank you.  William L. Ramseyer', '44:59', "Great interview i would say. Most motivating fact is that he didn't regret the mistakes he made. Excelent answer. Thank you for sharing this podcast."]

The evolution of non-lethal weapon is the true human proof and machine proof model! Imagine a prison outbreak... you simple incapacitate everyone, then just go inside to complete the retake of control! or air raids! you simple incapacitate the hole area without needing to reflect uppon killing or not! The first major mistake we are permiting at this stage of human evolution is to even consider the possibility of taken others life! if you could send that to mister moyes, i would gladly hear of him how we could rethink this!", 'A very nice talk on problems of the rates of human involvement and problems of the scale, but I'd like to go here a little deeper and touch another subject that _already_ seems to raise issues in some fields and the will certainly be relevant for autonomous weapons systems - AI-AI interaction and interaction with the enemy's AI. My thoughts are below and I will, of course, participate in a discussion in comments if someone has further ideas:

_Brief background_: there have been multiple proof-of-concept studies done on tricking an AI into making a false classification (e.g. "Adversarial Patch", by T. Brown, et. al, Dec 2017, you can find it on arxiv). Basically, they showed that having enough information on the structure of an image recognition algorithm, we can design stickers that will confuse the model. For example, you have a picture of bananas on a table and AI classifies them as "bananas on a table", but if you introduce a specific sticker to the image (even when it is small relative to bananas themselves), the model with almost absolute confidence will say that the image is of a toaster.

This possibility already causes problems in autonomous vehicles field, since people started designing stickers that when put on a road sign will cause a misclassification. Now, this issue can be addressed pretty successfully (imho) by keeping an updated openly distributed database of street sign locations, so a car can validate it's an assumption there, and by letting a car access a subset of relevant parameters from the last couple of cars that passed here to compare an assumption to what other algorithms had (IoT should help). 

However, issues with the military are much more complex as they imply highest degrees of confidentiality.

_Case_: assume you have a "counselling" algorithm of large scale that's designed to analyse the big picture of a particular battlefield to help you navigate the resources and make strategic decisions. How far are we from a potential enemy reverse engineering your model using military intelligence data, data collected by analysing your behaviour and decision making in real life applications of the system etc., and designing a "noise attack" that will cause misclassifications on such scale?

Ultimately, the enemy would prefer a model that can make your drones target your own soldiers, but to me, it seems more likely that early applications of such attack systems that target enemies AI will be simpler and more of a "noise"-causing attacks. For example, to make you think that there are significant enemy forces being accumulated in some area suggesting a strike, while the area is actually empty... Or maybe it happened so that there is a school there?

Now let's go one step deeper. You know that your enemy might be capable of attacking your AIs this way. What's an obvious reaction? To me, that would be to develop more sophisticated algorithms that will validate that what seems to be a school bus is not actually a disguised tank. However, what are the chances of this model making a mistake and you shooting at a school bus? What are the chances that this validation model itself gets a "noise attack"?

_Discussion and my suggestions_: all this complexity will be further convoluted by lack of info, which makes it hard to differentiate whether a decision was an unfortunate mistake made by AI, whether it was an accident caused by enemy orchestrating a noise attack or it was an intentionally designed attack that has as its goal blaming you and your AI? In the world where information war becomes one of the main battlefield areas, the complexity of these issues and lack of information will give many opportunities to violate human rights codes for military or geopolitical advantages. Answering questions like "was there an intend?" and "who is responsible?" will be rather difficult and might take a lot of time, which is an issue in terms of the information war.

I have one possible solution (partial solution, of course, but just to start this discussion) that is basically going back to autonomous vehicles problem - having an agreement that every country that uses AI in the military must make _some types_ of data *public*. I can already see how hard it will be to negotiate and how many ways there are to avoid sharing any meaningful data or just trying to fake it. ['This is why the age of "Elon Musk" will come to an end.', 'I thought the first rule of physics was to not lie about having a physics degree', 'this is first principles https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5uLch5vepi4&t=145s&ab_channel=SPARK', 'Kudos to Kevin Rose', 'Hi Lex, thanks for your channel. I have a long expert question for the community that keeps bugging me and maybe someone can help me and discuss this. First of all, I love Musk and would love to understand his thinking better. So I am not trying to push beliefs onto anybody but am open to learn. Here are my thoughts:

Musk famously reasons from first principles and has fantastic success with it. Now as I read it, this idea means boiling it down to the bare essentials and reasoning upwards. 

In my understanding reasoning upwards to a more generalized rule equals inductive reasoning as suggested e.g. by John Stuart Mill (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mill%27s_Methods). 

When looking further into the first principles method though it seems to stem from Descartes and is supposedly a form of deduction - so not induction but its opposite. 

Now, I am really confused here since as far as I understand, reasoning upwards from a single instance to a new general rule and not be blinded by old false premises and assumptions is the generalization exactly the central aspect of inductive reasoning. 

So Musks example of questioning / "cartesian doubting" the battery price for the Teslas means: Not being blinded by the "common wisdom/rule" of how expensive batteries are which would deduce logically something like this: 

A --> All batteries are expensive (If this premise is true)
B --> You need batteries for your Tesla (And this premise is true)
ERGO C --> Your Teslas battery must be expensive, too. (Then the conclusion must be true as well)

But Musk doesn't follow this approach. Instead he looks at reality, sees cheap stock prices of the bare battery components and induces the more general rule that it must be possible to produce batteries much cheaper. 

A --> Batteries are made of several components
B --> These bare battery components are today much cheaper than they use to be 
ERGO C --> Today it is within reason to build batteries much cheaper and successfully create a car company on top of it

Isn't that inductive reasoning? I am looking forward to discuss this with you. If you like to write a mail, please state this here and I will PM you my mail-address.

['I enjoyed this conversation.', 'So, this was a very interesting interview... but it begs a number of questions:

*What about the gut-brain axis, emotional link? #NutritionalPsychiatry and #BrainEnergy are a thing; why haven't we begun to discuss protocols for predicting (& strategically planning, for social sciences & statistical developments of) emotions using nutritional neuropsychiatry?
We can do a lot of emotional prediction (*including such things as, crowd control, preventing mob violence, and preventing sexual aggression) based on simple statistical surveys & analysis of nutritional&diet quality of a location or population.
Not all emotions are created in the brain. Think about it: where does seretonin develop? How does one's emotions change after a good meal, or after a bad one? What about when they have IBS (irritable bowel syndrome) or some such similar physical ailment where the waste in the body is literally leaking into the blood stream through holes in the gut/colon microbiome, and how does this affect emotions?
*Nutritional Delivery Matters. When nutrients are more bio-available the body functions better, and the whole system improves. Why isn't this holistic ideal being included in the conversation?
I mean, she did include "metabolic costs" as a variable in emotional function... but I feel she was incredibly lacking in depth. Maybe given the audience.

I just think this superficial facial expression and visual analysis is so cheap and limited. It is appallingly, shockingly inaccurate.

*Also: What about the emotional-vibrational scale?
We have tools such as heat maps and musical scales / acoustic listening / radar / sonar / etc. for visually mapping using heat and sound (*or other environmental chemical, even a stress hormone or sweat measured produces a distinct scent and chemical production in the environment, which can be measured objectively and interpreted using data analysis).
Why aren't we using these tools to measure emotional intelligence? And coordinate social harmony like you would a musical ensemble, or band.

*Memories are held in cellular memory; i.e., the body keeps the score.
We have to look at: cellular garbage collection and removal, techniques for emotional therapy such as EFT (tapping) and musical therapy (*look at Dr. Emoto's water droplet experiments and the fact the human body is >70% water, can be easily manipulated. ["I see a lot of concern, especially from animators, that tools like this will eventually make them obsolete.

This isn't a replacement for someone that knows how to animate, nor someone who can draw. Tools constantly evolve, but making something visually captivating always requires those same core skills. It still takes an artist to make art. That hasn't changed.

What we figured out here is a very advanced form of old-fashioned rotoscoping. Animation takes a lot of forms; Traditional, 3d, stop-motion... They all have different strengths, and enable different stories. Our method here isn't a replacement, but an attempt at something new.

What excites me is that this tech makes it easier to bring my visual ideas to life. Ideas that were otherwise impossible. When I said this democratizes animation, I'm referring to the near-insurmountable mountain of work needed to make a full-length narrative animation. Currently that requires large studios and large budgets. Doing it on your own is nearly impossible.

But I see potential in these tools to change that! That's what I'm so excited about. Imagine one person, or a few friends, bringing their crazy ideas to life. Imagine if a traditional animator could automatically have their drawings inked and colored. Imagine eliminating the uncanny valley on cgi faces. These tools have the potential to do that. We're trying to figure out how, and sharing our journey. If we want community-controlled AI tools, we need to develop them as a community, otherwise they become proprietary tools locked behind a company.

And yes, this can be done with your own style. We trained our model, not from hundreds of artists, but from ONE film- Vampire Hunter D Bloodlust.  We've been very open about this, and I think it's important to be. But this is also an experiment and a loving parody of this era of anime. I consider it no less ethical than the countless other videos on our channel that borrow from pop culture to tell their story.

Sudden change can be scary, especially if it feels like your passion or livelihood is on the line. But that's why we're out here exploring it. Hopefully we can help shine a light into the fog for everyone.
-Niko", 'Missed out on the shirt', 'These tools can create a stunning cgi thing movies with only one guy.  I can imagine it! its so excting!! This is potentialy can flash the old good super expensive animation productions. Pretty cool work team! üî•üî•üî•', 'Thats amazing', 'Was it just me or are those candles moving from the wrong side of the screen. (right to left)', 'cool! i lost all respect for corridor!', "it's been something else seeing ppl lose their minds and say AI = death of animation/artists, clearly having no idea about anything. No, AI animation/art will not mean all artists will be jobless and unneeded, also it will not mean all art/animated will be AI generated. This is simply another tool that will be used and artists will always be in demand, even in the case of companies using AI to generate animation/art, they will still need animators/artists to oversee that and manage the AI tool (i.e. artist/animator jobs will change, not be eliminated). 

so ya, people crying over AI animation/art tools and calling end times for animator/artists need to stop and actually look at things properly, instead of doomsaying. The keyword here being - adapt. No way are AI tools for art/animation generation going to be banned, outlawed or w.e as you simply can't stop these tools and programs from spreading, so you have to adapt to the change. 

New technology has always brought about disruption and change, those who succeed are the ones who adapt to the times instead of being defeatist about it.", 'Just changed anime', 'You kind of sell this as "bress button, receive anime", but clearly you still do a lot of actual work to get there. I realize that it's still a lot more accessible than hand drawing everything, but it's not quite just type "anime rock paper scissors" into a text box and getting a finished piece back. You wrote a script, you made costumes, you filmed your actors, you made screenshots of the anime you wanted to emulate, you taught several AI models, you ran your footage through those models, you created backgrounds, and you composited your background and foregrounds and applied corrections and filters on them. 

It's not a 100-person crew working for years, but it's not nothing. And it's not something "the average person" can "just" do.', 'Pioneers']

["i believe you guys are missing the point. the visual aspect have nothing to do with why Hollywood adaptation of anime sucks. the core problem is that when an anime series is adapted into live action, it is usually done so in the form of a feature film. Why is that the core problem you ask? Cuz anime relies heavily on their characters and world building to carry the narrative through. while feature films do to its more restrictive and shorter time slots relies on the story plot and its philosophical conflict to carry its narrative through. since the story plot and philosophical conflicts of an anime is built around the characters and world itself something that a shorter 2 hrs or less feature film can't really focus on you can see the problem here. if an anime series or even a tv show is adapted into a feature film, everything that makes it great in the first place will have to be taken out to fit the restrictive time slot. imagine if a tv show like Westworld or breaking bad was to be adapted into a feature film and the entirety of the story which is built around the characters and world itself had to be fitted into 2 hours. that wouldn't be very good now would it. these facts and the fact that some anime story concept  only work in a cartoon but would make absolutely no sense in live action film is the reason why Hollywood adaptation sucks.", 'Thank you Corridor To exposed Hollywood Bullsh*t they Done over the years', 'Too much internal monologue is a problem in live action. Film is a visual medium and exposition should be told through visuals rather than having it explained to us. In anime it works as a way for our characters to make the fight more interesting since the shots are so basic. In live action they could do it if they simplify the shots. The original Star Wars lightsaber duals are the best at how to do something similar to anime. The dialogue between characters is more important than how cool they twirl their glow sticks. ‚ÄúNo I am your father‚Äù is better than the high ground line in rots, and reminds me of anime a lot.', 'they also try to exactly mirror the hairstyles a lot, which never really work for a live action. the main point of a live action is basically *anime but irl*, so to need that humane touch of reality, they need to alter some stuff. ALICE IN BORDERLAND did this perfectly', '06:40 Very true. Hollywood (actors) hate having the faces covered.', "I can't think of a live action internal dialogue that doesn't feel super corny. The Sherlock scene was mad corny. I always felt like the reason they do that in anime is because usually it's a mostly still frame of someone gritting their teeth, or relaxing, or posing, and it's giving the artists a little shortcut while the voiceover gives exposition. The tennis scene is a little different because they're doing something visual. If that was done in live action i think you could just have them speaking out loud under their breath. Maybe those are internal dialogues in the anime so the artist doesn't have to add lip synced animation to an already very dynamic scene. \n\nIn live action, I always feel like there should be a reason to hear something. Like in the Sherlock scene i think it would work better if he the voice was from a memory of a training scene shown earlier, maybe with like snippets of flashbacks. Or my preference is to show rather than tell, so like have his facial expressions convey what he's thinking in those moments. Honestly in that specific clip it doesn't really need any audio. Have him glance down and the camera focuses on the handkerchief in his hand, and then he looks back up and throws it for the distraction. Then show the other guy looking at the handkerchief and missing his punch while Sherlock goes for the cheek. Keep the slow-fast motion edits. All the inner dialogue does for me there is make it smug and corny.", "The problem with cowboy was the casting, John Cho is way too old and the jet guy is way too young looking, John is a way north eastern Korean cheek bones and chin looking dude playing a knife faced south Chinese guy (like donnie yen who same age as john) under 30 who doesn't have a fro that makes him look ajumma. As for jet, the dude looks like he is half spikes age, need some one with Morgan freeman or John Amos level face weathering and horse draw to get the broke down old cop jazz man not this knock off of Wesley snipe's Blade persona!", 'Hollywood teams don‚Äôt direct them, they get some random first timer to do it', 'The slow mo to show hit was one of my favorite bits from the loki pilot hopefully they use it more', 'Cowboy Bebop Live action was fire. ["Hey guys, thanks for watching!

Just wanted to add my thoughts for those out there who maybe don't even know what it is they WANT to learn in the first place.

When it comes to picking a direction it can feel daunting, and the possibilities endless, but I believe a great first step is trying to figure out where you want to be in one year, five years, and ten years from now. What brings you joy? What do you see others doing and think, ‚ÄúI want to do THAT‚Äù.

In the 3D world, for example, there‚Äôs so many different paths you can take from modeling, texturing, lighting, compositing, or even just being a generalist who does a little bit of everything. Each of these paths lead to different end goals and the same is true in almost any field. So before starting down one specific path think about what makes you tick, and most importantly what makes you happy.

As I mentioned in the video, my initial plan was to go to USC and become an editor at Warner Brothers. I had no other dreams of doing anything else, and getting rejected completely ruined my plans. But by leaning on the skills I‚Äôd learned in working towards that initial goal, I changed course and used those skills to spur me on to a new, adapted goal.

Things will always change, but picking an initial direction and starting to build momentum and discipline are sure fire ways to make progress on ANY path. Movement of any kind is better than remaining static.

All to say, you don‚Äôt have to pick with 100% accuracy right out the gate. You can always use the things you‚Äôve learned to adapt your goal as/if your interests change, but in that process you are still building the skills and discipline along the way that make that change of course much faster and easier.

Best of luck my friends!", 'Thanks this is extremely helpful guys...you guys are Awesome üí™üíõ', 'i watched this after i gave up on life... my bad', 'Wonderful and encouraging 

I‚Äôm 42 and just now wanting to start a new art in 3D animation and visual effects. Never done anything like it but I‚Äôm loving the learning experience.', "Honestly I needed this, I've been a Corridor fan for as long as I can remember. Came into the scene after binging FreddieW's videos and after that I've always wanted to get into VFX and making movies, I put that dream on hold for a while in order to struggle through my own path a bit but I think this video is really pushing me to pick it back up. The goal is to one day work with or maybe along side Corridor :P but I have a long way to go before I can seat with the greats. Thanks again for giving me inspiration, honestly if you guys hosted a VFX workshop or a class I'd sell everything I owned to pay for it so I can finally learn this. i have so many cool movie idea's and I just really want to express myself but I've never been able to sit down and take the time to make it happen.", 'im gonnadie alone with literally 0 chance of ever getting any job anywhere, or finding any friend, or anyone who loves me. etc. you should put some brackets in the title and say "only applies to lucky people with rich parents and no mental illness". goodbye', 'im gonnadie alone with literally 0 chance of ever getting any job anywhere, or finding any friend, or anyone who loves me. etc. you should put some brackets in the title and say "only applies to lucky people with rich parents and no mental illness"', 'Beautiful video!üíØ', '10/10 video', "Thanks so much for this video. G movies are bright and colourful. This Saw guy and being chained up does not look as nice as a sunshine and rainbows in a paddock full of ponies. With that said, a very young child does not know much, so it wouldn't seem so ominous to them. 

Phobias and fears have started from when someone was a child watching something that isn't bad, they simply didn't like it. Like the 'Cracks' lost media (it's found but you know what I mean). People had nightmares about something that was literally just a short animated film about cracks in a wall. Anything that merely looks frightening can create a long lastign fear of something. Every child is obviously different. 

If a child watches a movie where nothing bad happens besides people being chained up, they could develop an unhealthy obsession with chains and being bound by something. The parents would never figure out where it started. You shouldn't have to be too careful when making children's movies, but Im just saying no matter what, a movie can frighten a child. Our brain must have the ability to calculate a infinite amount of values just to render our sight.üòÇ', 'Yara G hamara to favorite Oreo hay laykin Jo ya izat afzai ap nay ki hay in ki Mayray Dill ki batien kah di hienüòÇüòÇüòÇüòÇ', "If you want to be entertained, this may be fine. If you want to learn something, you should watch @TheArtofCodeIsCool, which are actually educational. I realize now, that this looks like an ad or something, but yeah.. heh. He's mainly discussing Ray Marching, which is pretty interesting if one likes math.. and he doesn't try to be funny, which I find truly nice.", "My man is out here exasperated with 100 hour caustic renders, meanwhile I'm over here rendering a few minutes of video without any super crazy effects for the better part of 5 months.", 'still don‚Äôt know why photo tracer is thousand times fasterüòÇ. He just said it‚Äôs faster but no mathematical detail.', "I was working on that in uni decades ago. The reason caustics are hard is there's no obvious way to trace a path from the camera to the light through 3rd surfaces. Normally you trace from camera to surface and then you trace in the direction of each light to see if the patch of surface is illuminated. But if light is to come through reflection or refraction it could be coming through any path. You'd have to render the entire scene from the PoV each surface patch just to calculate 2nd level lighting. Or you could trace photons forward from the light, have them deposit on surfaces randomly like textures, and then trace the scene from the camera and hope you got enough photons. That's the slow technique that I worked on way back. You could do better with fancy sampling and compression of photons, or some differential approximation of path tracing, which I'm guessing form part of the new renderer."]

['This is nice, but a few historical details aren't quite right. I was part of the crew that made this - and I'm in that group photo you showed.

John did not go to England to measure the set and record where the lights were. Someone else got that info for us. Motion blur was invented in the Computer Division, and we were never part of ILM.

We rendered the highlights as a separate element so that ILM Optical could tweak them, and if you look carefully all of the floating bits of glass are slightly convex, which allowed a more pleasing reflection of the environment. (When Barry Levinson asked in dailies for it to look "more religious" we all panicked, but Dennis Muren just had Optical add 2 more clicks of diffusion to the glow pass.)

A detail you might like is that the candles and stands in the foreground of that tracking shot are all CGI.

That rack focus shot was so expensive to compute that I spent 2 weeks at CCI headquarters in Orange County rendering just the last 2/3 of that shot on borrowed computers overnight. Meanwhile, Bill Reeves (the bearded guy in the photo with John) rendered the first third. I had to fly down with two giant disk packs which each could hold about 300 Mb.

You should definitely read Alvy Ray Smith's book, "A Biography of the Pixel" to get this, and the rest of the history of computer graphics. It's terrific.', 'therwy', 'I hate Jordan so much', 'Lawnmower Man (1992)', 'No comments about the shardblade? I want one so bad.', 'You guys have the tech they didn‚Äôt have and yet doesn‚Äôt look near as close.', 'Honestly like especially with the dance moves, I cannot unsee Cody from Set it Off in Jordan xD', 'I would love to see if you guys could do a better CGI The Last Starfighter', 'killed this', "I would challenge you guys to spend a week immersing yourself in female oriented media, to see what you can learn about entertaining the opposite sex. I find this is a huge gap in ability and awareness among male filmmakers who seem content to just make content for the guys. I've always loved Batman but my daughter and I were so bored we walked out of the theatre at the last batman movie. It would benefit you guys to see what issues are more universal and what issues are more unique to your gender, and ours, in a generalized sense, to enhance and emphasize your skill in storytelling and reaching a broader audience if that is what you are going for."]

["I definitely believe people would be fooled by Clark Kent's disguise 'cause I wouldn't recognize my own mother if I bumped into her at the grocery store.

But given the face mask, I think this does more to prove that masks are an effective disguise.", 'I think the disguise works for some people because of their similar appearance to another person (like twins, stunt doubles, etc.) like in the third Matrix film with all of the Smiths. Without proper perception or understanding of which one is the actual Agent Smith you would never be able to tell; even with height variations and body sizes. For some others whose perception is very good, someone like Spy from TF2, or Loid Forger could rather convincingly fool many people without much effort (even without their masks).
And finally we come to ultra perception; people who are skilled enough in recognition, memory, intelligence and intuition - people who are good at disguise themselves. In order to fool someone like that would be nearly impossible for more than three interactions IF it was done right', 'The thing is with Superman and Clark Kent is that no one is really looking for Batman. They know who Superman is. Everyone knows he‚Äôs the kryptonian Kal-el and that he lives in the fortress of solitude. It‚Äôs like trying to think your one friend is Obama or something. Like, you know who Obama is and that he‚Äôs definitely not your friend trey. So you don‚Äôt even consider it a possibility. Why would people think Clark Kent is Superman when people know who Clark Kent is and people know who Superman is', "That Carpenter Brut t-shirt that Niko's rocking üëåüèº", "The biggest problem with Clark's & even Bruce's secret identities isn't that they would never work, it's that they only need to not work once.", 'I wore khakis and a red shirt into a target once and not only had random people come up to me to ask for help finding things in the store but also had one of the employees mistake me for someone who really did work there.', 'One thing with Superman is that he completely changes his posture and mannerisms as Clark Kent. It also kind of has the celebrity lookalike effect, where people write off the fact that they look alike as a coincidence. There were even real cases where celebrities lost their own lookalike contests.', "Very good for the change in attitude and body movements, but he exaggerates too much (he moves his head up and down a lot, it doesn't look very natural, draws a lot of attention) he has also put on much more than just glasses and a change of hairstyle (he wears a hat/cap and face mask), that could be considered cheating. Although, well, Clark arrived in Metropolis before Superman and did not try to fool an office of people who previously knew him. This is as if Clark had tried to trick his parents instead of some unknown office people far away from the town where he grew up and where he had just moved. 
In addition, in the interpretation of the best Superman in live action, Christopher Reeve, there is a lot of difference between Superman and Clark... it is practically unthinkable to associate Clark with Superman if you have not had both face to face and even in that case normally you only would think they are very similar but not the same person.", "Superman's disguise only works, because the people who knows him as superman, does not know Clark, and those who know him as clark, has not seen superman's face. Some people like the justice league does know that clark kent is superman. Many people who knows clark kent personally, mostly do not see supermans face clearly, and if they do, they know superman's secret identity", 'Well, these people hang out with him every day‚Ä¶ no one really hangs out with Superman‚Ä¶ even if someone sees similarities, you can never truly be sure of anything. Not to mention sometimes people can just look alike‚Ä¶ shit, the actor that plays Superman actually goes outside with an actual Superman shirt and people don‚Äôt know it‚Äôs him‚Ä¶ you just don‚Äôt expect it']

For example, when the Nox open the portal, it's entirely different so that it doesn't have any protrusions. It's done that way to show that the Nox are so advanced they can open portals with just their minds, unlike the petty underlings of the galaxies.

See here: /watch?v=X18XGc1OHfk", 'The big red dog is now out and the part where the children is on dogs back- that is completely different quality', '8:08  I have two questions about not just the movie _Stargate,_ but also its TV spin-offs _Stargate SG-1_ and _Stargate Atlantis._

- Stargate Command (SGC) regularly uses various shades of *green* camouflage for their equipment and clothing, but then the various visual effects and lighting used for the gate's portal/event horizon are *blue* which inevitably blends with that green.  _How exactly_ did the movie and shows accommodate this when doing their greenscreen/bluescreen cut-outs in either "the gate room", not to mention on-location where there's greenery all around???

- When an object or person moves into/comes out of the gate's event horizon, it gets cut-off from the camera's POV; obviously removed in editing.  But my question is:  _how_ do the VFX artists know _exactly where_ to do that cutting-off when there are no visual markers on a _moving_ actor/object, as well as accommodating both solid objects and wrinkles in clothing?  Does the interior edge of the Stargate 'prop' have a mass of red laser markers (appearing similar to bar code scanners on-set) drawing red lines at a specific point that is then used as the reference markers that the VFX artists can then remove in post?
(Red laser markers are the only thing I can think of, but the downside is the refraction at _the contact points_ would show and you'd have to somehow paint _that_ out as well, so I don't have a solid guess.  Plus, _any_ laser markers _bright enough to be seen on camera,_ and in a ring configuration, would be expensive on a TV budget, not to mention a visual hazard for everyone on-set!)', 'Good old StarGate.', 'Please react to zathura its an older movie i watched as  a kid and i want to see your opinion on the VFX. warning there a bit iffy sometimes.', '13:01 shoulda been wild wild west', 'I watched and enjoyed Clifford the Big Red Dog on PBS growing up and I was irritated by this movie after seeing the trailer and I wish they would have stayed in line with the book and show and give kids the many moral life lessons (which was the point and why it was loved as the book and the show) and why I don‚Äôt care for this live action Clifford movie and the garbage Space Jam 2 that I refuse to watch lol.

The lighting, grading and shaders I thought looked better on the 2008 Hulk. I'm sure if we were to put them in the same environment next to each other, you could tell the 2017-2022 Hulk is probably technically more detailed. But just because he's more detailed doesn't mean he's a better character model. I'm fairly certain the 2008 one also had pores, but they're much more toned down and that honestly makes it look like he's got monster skin, which I would think should be the point, not to just be an oversized man (that is not what the Hulk is). ['I learned photography in high school because my school offered an analog photography class for whatever reason. We shot then developed all of our film in a dark room so it was definitely an experience. 

Analog photography just hits different. You have to put way more thought into the shot. You don‚Äôt know if it turned out. If you develop it yourself, the whole image feels like yours. It‚Äôs just a fun experience. It makes photography feel like a hobby. 

With digital you can easily just rapid fire a bunch of shots and keep the best with very little cost. Its great for capturing moments but definitely doesn‚Äôt feel the same from a photography point of view. It‚Äôs much more sterile and simplistic in a sense.', 'This is now Corridor Physical', "I love to shoot in film but really can't keep up with the price these days anymore.", 'Hallway Analog.', 'I miss shooting on film! ["Beyond the fact that this video is about CGI, it's marvelous for just contextualizing the real life constraints of creating great works. And in doing so, inspires as much as it empathizes. All my judgmental biases are now in their proper places. Great job on this one.", "I'm torn on the blade runner CGI woman.  Its impressive.  But to me its more similar to a photorealistic painting or drawing, than it is to a photorealistic moving character because the character is so expressionless.   

They solved the problem of creating a photorealistic CGI person by removing the facial animations that make recreating a human so difficult, not by actually recreating them.", 'is this the same script for wrens ted talk?', 'Love the Brandon Sanderson shoutout', 'this guy is so passionate about cgiüòÇüòÇüòÇüòÇ', 'Still baffles me today how people speak highly of cartoony mcu cgi and ignores man of steel.', "There's only one moment of Tron: Legacy I didn't like and it was the CGI version of Jeff Bridges' character in the real world. Accepting that Clu, Tron, and other characters being in the Uncanny Valley worked for the movie because we knew those characters were from a digital world. But for a young Jeff Bridges to be CGI felt really awkward and uncomfortable...especially with how much they focused on him in that part. Outside of that, I think Tron: Legacy did a really solid job overall visually.

The big thing that stands out to me with CGI usage in the modern era is how smooth and fluid motions are...we've gotten pretty good at simulating material moving, but for actual human mobility, there's still this really weird fluidness to any and all movement that makes it incredibly obvious that something is CGI.", 'Hold your tongue, Transformers cgi is some of the best there is', "Hey Wren, I'm just finishing the Wheel of Time saga where Sanderson also took over the last parts. It's a delight!", 'I was wondering why I herd this before and then I remembered his ted talk']

['I'm one of the VFX artist credited for the " interior rolling ball scene" in THE ROBOT.
At start we did got a very detail head scan model of the antagonist but ended up never used, as the rendering was deemed too heavy for the studio. Only low poly version was used whenever he did any ridiculous moves. 
The most challenging part of the scene is the intense flashing light. It ruins camera tracking. we have to painstakingly fix the track & match every single flashlight for the CG stunts by hand.
P.s. the movie's VFX was actually outsourced  to dozens of small studio in hong kong, so as you can see the quality vary A LOT between shots.', "It's Tollywood", 'You will laugh more if you will see the indian serialsüòÇ', 'Sigham is much better than mission impossible', 'Watch ra-one movie VFX', "It's Bollywood bro it's telegu industry", 'this is awesome stuff', 'Please react on 2.0, brahmastra,hanuman trailer', 'Someone tell these fucking guys tht the 1st 2 clips r not from fucking Bollywood üò≠üò≠üò≠üò≠üò≠', 'Guys checkout ra.one(2011) and brahmastra(2022)']

Also, love Clint's direction.", 'I also have high-functioning autism, and he describes it pretty spot on. I was always much more comfortable talking with my teachers than my fellow students, and even to this day I rarely if ever go anywhere without a book to read in case I get bored.

I found that a good way to adapt with my autism is, when I meet a new person I'm going to be spending a lot of time with, like in my workplace or in public, I just tell them, "Hey, my name's such-and-such and I have high-functioning autism, so I apologize ahead of time if I do something to accidentally offend you or make you uncomfortable. Just let me know about it and I'll stop doing that thing." And most people are just like, "Oh, that's cool. Thanks for letting me know" or "Yeah, that makes sense. Will do".

Admittedly, it only worked to help others be comfortable with my quirks once I myself was comfortable with my quirks, but the vast majority of people I meet (which admittedly aren't very many due to my autism, so maybe not the best sample size) are much more comfortable once they can identify what it is that makes me different.

There's been times where I haven't told people, and they just sit and wonder what it is about me that seems . . . slightly off. And they dwell on it, and ponder it, and it comes to define how they think about me: "the weird guy". But once you lay the cards on the table and say, "I have high-functioning autism, and that's why I'm a little weird", the first group, those that know about high-functioning autism, go, "Oh, yeah, that makes sense" and they move on to get to know me as a person with interests and hobbies. And those that don't know about high-functioning autism, the second group, some of them go, "Oh, okay, it's a known thing, then. Fair enough", and some of them go and look up a little about high-functioning autism and then they go, "Oh, yeah, that makes sense" and they move on to get to know me as a person like the first group.

And anyone who makes fun of me for being autistic are just assholes and not people I want to hang out with anyway. It also helps that high-functioning autism has given me an excellent memory and intelligence, and usually when I meet them joke for joke, they quickly back down.']

Since greed is what drives people nowadays, landlords start to throw out the people that helped that area prosper (the initial low rent) either by making the rent unbearable to the locals or by selling the building to some wealthy company that then does the same (because they want richer residents to make their profit grow).

['This video is incorrect. We know about direct ads because we also have them, it's what informed us to make that video, because when we get the yellow mark our direct ads still DO NOT run. 

For clarity, our MCN sells ads directly on our content, just like ABC does on Kimmel, but YouTube is always the middle man. They are completely involved in the process and it uses their ad system. They make 45% on all sales and approve all sales, just like regular ads. The only difference here, which has already been confirmed to us by YouTube, is that Jimmy Kimmel (and a select few other channels, mostly owned by big media) have special exceptions that bypass their ad policy so they would never be demonetized. Since our video has been posted, they have confirmed to us that they are working to close that exception because their ad policy should be consistently enforced across the board.

Regarding their comments about censorship. What else would you call it? Rewarding some speech and punishing others? Sure they are not straight up silencing them, but they are heavily dissuading them from making a type of content. There is also a good chance the algorithm promotes them far less once they've been demonetized and marked as "problematic" by classifiers. Meanwhile Jimmy Kimmel is #1 trending and full ads.', 'Ahh so the problem is still a double standard just a different one', 'how does this not have more veiws?!?', 'H3h3 is wrong about everything. Hate that shit.', 'I wonder how many people actually watched this right to the last second? I miss this kind of thing, where people with opposing opinions and ideas can have a discussion in a calm and thoughtful way, its something that is starting to become a rarity in the world i think.', 'How can such amazing artists have such terrible taste in hats.', 'Shame that time proved H3 hypocrites', 'I think that even a channel that does not run a single ad has the potential to raise the value of the youtube product and should therefore get paid.', 'You guys are wrong.', 'VFX ARTISTS DO YOUTUBE DRAMA?']

['Hey Everyone! *Parts list for the drone is in the description!* _Explanation here_:

The drone I built is a modified Inductrix Blade, most commonly referred to as a "Tiny Whoop". You can buy fully built kits, DIY kits, or buy the individual parts and assemble it together like I did. You will also need a radio transmitter (the controller) and some FPV goggles to view the camera feed. You can also just use a little monitor screen that has a radio antenna attached. I already had these from when I started getting into racing drones last year. If you go the build-it-yourself route you will want to watch a lot of tutorials and will need a soldering iron. It wasn't as hard as I expected it to be though ;)

I was flying in what's called "*Acro*" mode, meaning that it does *_not_* fly like a DJI drone. If you set it to "level" mode, it will behave that way, but in acro mode it will not self-correct so you can easily do things like flips and barrel rolls, but also makes it way more difficult to fly. If you press forward on the sticks, it will continue to go forward until it's upside down haha. I've started learning how to do flips and stuff but I need to set better PIDs.

The main components of the drone are the airframe, props, motors, flight controller (brain), camera, and batteries. I provided links to everything I could in the description. You can choose more powerful motors which will give you more agility and ability to do flips. I went with the middle-power motors for now but will probably upgrade soon. ALSO, the radio antenna on my camera is a linear one rather than the cloverleaf configuration normally seen as default with the tiny whoops, because it's supposedly harder to break. The bigger antennas break easily. I also hot-glued some tooth-picks from the antenna to the frame for added support. 
Good luck everyone!', "With tiny stuff like that you're supposed to use a special soldering tip they are like super fine-tips idk how you did it with that thing.  You can't be too bad at it if you accomplished that lol", "His grandfather's name was Shia.  He was from a time when men would just DOOOO ITTTTTT", 'Nick, 1:38 - "Ugh, my feet are wet."

['Freebooting in this context was coined by Brady Haran on the podcast Hello Internet', 'What infuriates me is seeing those freebooters add their own watermarks to content they did not create, without even crediting the owner.', "I've created a new website to fight this exact problem - https://spotter.tech - You can search any video in the entire web. It is still in Beta mode so you can only search videos within Facebook and YouTube. Feel free to give it a try ;)", "Reddit could potentially be an issue but it doesn't seem to currently be a large one. The posters are not actively making anything money off of the post and neither is reddit since they don't typically make any money. Imgur is the furthest thing from an issue, the top comment is almost always the source if it isn't included in the little about section under the post.  Facebook on the other hand is the poster child for the problem that is freebooting. This is a system that promotes people to post content to their own video player, in what world does that sentence translate to anything but re-uploading an already existing video. Compared to the number of users facebook has the number of original artists is pretty small. Then you have to go even deeper to find those who are creating in any way that involves a video format. This is the root of why facebook is so riddled with freebooting. That and that facebook makes money off freebooters and has no motivation to stop them. For example you guys may post/share to facebook sometimes, but you are never going to relocate there (along with pretty much all bigger names on youtube). Your freebooters however are going to upload as much of your content as they think they can make money on, so facebook gets to make money of off you that they wouldn't normally make.", "I think reddit does support freebooting, but often links go to the source of the video, and imgur is pretty good on providing a source link as well. Ive seen reddit users get upset at OP's when they take credit for others work as well. So yes, technically reddit may support freebooting, but the OP's don't really make money from it. As you've said, it pales in comparison to Facebook and many other freebooting websites.", "I saw 'game of war',a phone game, use your age of empire video on one of their ads without giving you guys credit. I hate phone app ads enough but using other people's content pisses me off even more so.", '5 seconds of gif==theft?', "This is super common. I've been on Facebook and 9GAG for a while and I've seen GIFs or pictures with no link to the original content when I'm interested in what it was. Facebook is probably the worst because one of my friends shared a video with the whole Deadpool movie shown.", "Yeah, Reddit's a freebooting paradise, but Facebook takes it up a whole nother shitstained notch by allowing Freebooters to make money off of content they stole.", 'never give up guys!']

['But everything changed‚Ä¶ 
Until *2014* , when *‚ÄùJohn Wick‚Äù* shot theatres‚Ä¶', 'yes', 'no one beats the Zatochi films.', 'Interstellar docking scene... what a thrilling bit of action!', 'The Indiana Jones series, Rambo series, all Bruce Lee films, Terminator 1, 2 and yes, even Dark Fate, Commando, Predator 1 and 2, ALIENS, The Grandmaster, and select martial arts films from Tony Jaa and Jeeja Yanin have the greatest action scenes ever put on film. Even movies you wouldn't think of, like Ben-Hur 1959, easily has one of the top 5 action sequences of all time in the chariot race. Better than a lot of the "good examples" in this video. My selects are more than just spectacle and technique (which you can teach a dog). It's the characters and emotion that sell them all. You showing Luke vs. Vader from ROTJ was a great example, so good job on that.

And Glory 1989's Fort Wagner assault >>>>>>> Saving Private Ryan's D-Day opening. Spielberg, once known for clean and non-shaky action scenes, truly disappointed me that year.', "I saw The Hitman's Bodyguard today and oh my God. The color grading, fake police cars and uniforms for a nearly 70 million dollar film (I live in the Netherlands, the fake police cars really bothered and distracted me) and the shaky camera fights really ruined the movie. Even though the movie itself wasn't super sucky. I often even wondered whether they were actually filming in the Netherlands or not. That's how distracting some of those details were. Made me wonder if they filmed some of it in Belgium or France instead.", "i will say that as i was making movies, my friend said to me, no put that there and this here.. and i was like, but it doesn't fit the rythmn of your movie ! and he was like, i know what i want ! but everytimes i thoguht, but your film has a rythmn and you are just ignore it for the sake of shots ! and i think that's the problem with most movies now a days... they want fast action but fast action means we see less and less, and thats why they take that road, they want fast movement, but do not consider their audiences at all. i preffer slower movies that can accelrate or slow down while still seeing the action and the environment then just scenes with great shot that have no context.

its all about rythmn really.  take this example... i wanna put an intro to a youtube channel documentary videos... i could pull off tons of footage and wrender them as a 1 minute long intro. but is that really an intro ? no, to me a great intro is not long... i'm talking about 10 to 15 seconds long. how much can i put into that ? so i have these videos showing for a second and then fading as another shot comes in. but heres the trick... 1 second is not long enough for context ! so now where i wanted 10 shots, i'm down to 5 because now i'm down to 2 seconds each shot. that's rythmn. 

question you should really be asking yourselves is... if i know nothing of the movie or the scene... audience who never saw the footage... would i know what's hapenning ? if the answer is no, then you are off rythmn ! imagine a boxing match where both people are trying to be on their own rythmn. the winner is the one who sucessfully get the other into his rythmn... same happens here... you are trying to bring the audience into your rythmn. so yeah, don't throw your rythmn off just because of a cool shot you absolutely want in your film !", "Clearly they haven't seen Indian movies, most of them are mixture of bullshit.", 'Great video!', 'Are you implying that 30 years ago actions scenes never sucked.  Ever watch Captain Kirk fight?']

Give me more Wren!!', 'How much wrendering did wren do?', "if you don't have a phone you should probably get a phone lmao", 'omg Sam used to be so thin', 'helpful!', 'heck', 'I used to have the problem of dreaming up a project, but never starting it because of high expectations. Then I\'d get bored with that and "start" a new project. So I figured I\'d address people out there that struggle with that problem. Although I\'m not sure if there\'s any tips I can give you that they haven\'t already... like "finish what you start", I CAN say, however, that you definitely grow out of that stage. And I think it comes when you DO finally finish something, and realize how awesome it feels, and you begin to see how much time you\'ve wasted not finishing things (or not even starting things in many cases). Also think about the fact that you have plenty of time to accomplish many projects throughout your life. Don\'t get wrapped up in thinking your first project has to be your Academy Award-nominated piece. Really understand that making projects is the way you grow. Just like anything else in life: practice, practice, practice. Thinking that your first projects are going to be perfect (no matter how much you think they can be), is what will kill you in the end. It will keep you from ever finishing because things will not be living up to the expectation in your mind of how the project should be going. Just HAVE FUN! That\'s the ultimate tip. Pretend like you\'re a kid again making home movies (if you did that sort of thing). There are people in Hollywood making millions off of movies and they\'re still not happy (for one, because money doesn\'t satisfy if that was their goal), but for two because they\'ve lost the enjoyment that their former selves got from making movies. I think a main reason is perfectionism and crowd pleasing. You become so focused on the outcome of your movie instead of the enjoyable process. Which leads to what I\'ve already said: Extremely high expectations that can\'t be met. And as much fun as they are when they rarely come around, movies don\'t NEED to be perfect. Critics have kind of ruined movies in a way. We\'ve turned what was supposed to be an artistic form of escapism into a list of standards that have to be met. Even people watching movies these days can\'t fully enjoy them because we\'re analyzing them the whole time. Have fun, be a kid, make some magic.', 'nice!', 'Just do it!!  üòÇ']

Is it just as simple as connecting the panning two clips. ', "Thought I'd make a list of the summary points for myself and others to write down. (And carry with me whenever I try to direct. Haha.)

‚òª Clear direction (Good, clear communication.)
‚òª Don't always stick to the script (Improvise, but make sure you're prepared if it doesn't work out.)
‚òª Study other styles to learn yours (Learn from directors you like.)
‚òª Take your time and be efficient (A slow, good decision is always better than a fast, bad one.)
‚òª Find a clear way to communicate your goal (Have a shot list, story board, or some way to easily portray your ideas for your team.)
‚òª Friends can help make your life easier (It's hard to focus on both camera angles/setup and the acting at the same time. Find someone else to help you shoot, you'll need them at times.)
‚òª Viewfinders are super helpful on set (Use tools--like your fingers or a viewfinder--to help you set up your shot.)
‚òª Spend your time wisely (Because it's limited--know when to move on.)
‚òª Avoid fights on set (It looks bad, and sets a bad example. If you have to, take them aside to discuss it privately)
‚òª Stay hydrated (And now you're all wet.)
‚òª Don't worry about the gear you want. Focus on the gear you need.
‚òª Respect and take care of your team. (Instead of being demanding, like a boss, nurture and coach them.)
‚òª Actors need motivations, not just marks. (Don't do an actor's job for them--instead of telling them how to do it, help them understand *_why_* they're doing a scene.)
‚òª Respect your actor's process. (Help them. Gain their trust and respect.)
‚òª Get it done, move on to your next idea. (Reiteration of spend your time wisely. Don't burn yourself out. Finishing something allows you to try new things, and learn from experience.)", "2:06- there is tether's mask in the background", 'what is the editing effect ???']

travelwithdrone.com', 'When you play the Game of Drones, you either win... or it crashes and your platoon\xa0has to go out and find that damn thing.', 'niko <3', "Only just now watching this video and I can't help but question if it wasn't the battery and radio interference. I have no clue what those towers are but given their location and the clear amount of money put into them I would almost venture to guess they are a mix of Public Safety, Commercial, and probably some Amateur HAM. Basically, I could easily see it as being a mixture of the Niko trying to get it as close to them as he could; The landing preset kicking in, and radio interference confusing the drone. It could be as simple as the battery kicking in the preset with a mixture of the crosswind or a radio frequency that wasn't active prior to the crash getting a heavy load of traffic.

Admittedly, I doubt my own theory about a burst of radio interference, however I did want to throw out some credence to Sam's speculation. If there was a repeater on that tower that suddenly kicked to life with heavy traffic the sheer power put out by the transmission could potentially screw with any signal coming from the control to the Drone. Again, I doubt my own theory because I would hope the makers of that Drone would have researched possible frequencies and selected one that would avoid situations like this but stranger things happen."]

Delivering that tangible, practical information üëèüèΩ  üëèüèΩ', "How much of this would you say can be incorporated into a written story, one that may not be filmed, but left on paper? Or what would you change with your explanation when it comes to a written story. I doubt what I'm writing will ever be acted out (considering it would take way too long for just myself and a handful of people to even try to start it on our own), but I'd just like to get some pointers on how to simply *write* a good story.", "one of my Cinematic Arts lecturers taught me how to create a context of a story using the PEACE formation:

P - Protagonist/Problem: the main character of a story who either change for the better, or stay for the worse with a problem that slowly gets worse and worse.

E- Environment: an environment the protagonist would be in is something that would take them out of their comfort zone, and basically enhance their problems to become even worse. 

A- Antagonist: a person involved in the story that's the sole reason as to what drives the protagonist forward. The one who never changes, but challenges the protagonist to change.

C- Collision: The Protagonist and Antagonist confronts one another for a final battle that would ultimately decide their fate for the future

E- Ending: The end of the story with the conclusive fate of both character's future. (pro tip: the more tragic your stories are, the more memorable the story is.)", "Could you guys make a video on how to get where you guys are right now? (Career wise) Because that's Almosen exactly what I want to do....like....with life ^^", 'So much inspiration >.< :D']

["I find these endlessly entertaining for some reason, so here are few bonus reasons why rocks float in the air (according to GPT-3, by OpenAI):

- In the planet's gravity, rocks are heavier than air. But since there is no gravity in the air ~because it's not a planet~ the rocks float.
- Some rocks, such as pumice have an air pocket in the centre. The air pocket creates buoyancy, which makes the rock float.
- Rocks float in the air because they are not affected by forces such as gravity, which pull other objects downwards.
- The rocks are not floating in the air, they are floating on the ground.
- The rocks are caught in the updraught, causing them to float.", 'Amaze', "Damn Astroneer 2 lookin' pretty dope.", "I've got to say, I am perpetually impressed by your videos. ['What programing lenguage you used?', "Probably too late to the party, but those patterns emerging at 5:30 or so are called hypotrochoids iirc, they're the patterns drawn by spirographs. Where a big circle has a smaller circle attached, which both rotate, and the smaller circle hold a 'pen' at some distance from it's center. This system seems to have a lot in common with orbital mechanics, with the centre point of the large circle working as a sun or large mass, the small circle's centre being the position of a smaller orbitting mass, and the position of the pen acting as a moon or satellite.

Here the equation they use:
        r1 is the radius of the large circle, r2 the small circle, d is the distance of the pen from the centre of the small circle, and a is theta, the difference in angle from the horizontal plane, the x axis in            my case.
        x = (r1 - r2) * math.cos( (r2 / r1) * a ) + d * math.cos( ( 1 - ( r2 / r1)) * a) 
        y = (r1 -  r2) * math.sin( (r2 / r1) * a ) - d * math.sin( ( 1 - ( r2 / r1)) * a)", 'Better than no mans sky on release', '8:50 I was gonna comment that the system looked almost IDENTICAL to the outer wilds lol', 'I could watch your stuff all day! I have always wanted to make a space game and make it look like it is made out of paper and call it Papercraft. The player could also make stuff out of paper like origami and maybe scissors and glue :D look a little like Kubo and the two strings paper stuff.', "Put it on los&android and you'll be billion air", 'he just made ksp 3', 'How did you render the future paths of the planets when there were more than three', '"jigeling like there is no tomorw" killed me', '7:20 Fun Fact: Thats actually what people like Johannes Kepler were thinking when they saw the orbit of Mars']

["Hello, sorry for the rather short episode today! Spent a lot of time experimenting with this, but didn't end up with much to show for it unfortunately.
I think coding as a gameplay mechanic is a really interesting concept, but I struggled to make something fun out of it. Would love some recommendations for games to play, if you know any games which do it well?

Finally, in case anyone here is wondering about the source-code to the last coding adventure (since I've been promising to upload it for a while) -- I'm probably going to start working on a part 2 of the ecosystem sim in the next few weeks, and I'll try tidy up the project and release it then.", 'Just found your channel today, and you've made me want to download unity again. I tried once long ago (I have always dreamed of making a video game ever since I was a little kid with an N64), and I've always been able to come up with neat ideas for different mechanics (especially for RPGs and the like), but the actual nuts and bolts of it all was just a little bit much to take in at once. Since then, I have gained more experience with small projects (making minecraft mods, following a roguelike tutorial using Python, messing around in Blender, that type of thing), but you've really inspired me today. This is a type of game I have always wanted to play but could never find one that was decent enough. I envision something that someone who doesn't code at all could sit down and actually have fun playing instead of spending three hours following an online (or in-game) tutorial just to be able to get past the first puzzle. I picture something that can present a problem that is complex enough to make a professional programmer scratch their head a bit, but that your average layman could also solve given enough time and clues.

You could have a setting where you work for some manufacturer of automated machinery set in the not-so-distant future. Your goal is to debug the faulty machines that have been returned to the company. You'd have a little test bed set up specific to whatever machine it is you're working on, and a console displaying the current program that is loaded onto the machine, which can be edited, compiled, and re-uploaded to the machine. Your job would be to try and fiddle with the code, then test the machine to make sure it runs properly, then send it back as a refurbished product. You could make it interesting and allow the player to send out something that is still incorrect, causing it to be returned again, opening the door to a sort of meta game where your work influences the success of the company and what contracts they can obtain, and maybe you can even get fired, and that would be how you lose. 

You could even have the "correct" program available to the player, in the form of reference documents, which could also be edited by the player (adding notes, or creating entirely new documentation for some piece of coding the player came up with). The first several "levels" would be small syntax errors in the code (missing parentheses/brackets/semicolons, mis-capitalized letters, etc), so that way you could slowly ease the player into formatting and what looks right and what doesn't. As you progress through the game, you get more and more complex errors (missing lines of code, arithmetic errors and so on), and less and less help from your reference documents (maybe the paper only describes the root nature of a function, but the problem requires you to string several functions together in a creative way, or maybe your reference displays the code in C# but you're trying to work with Python, or something like that). You could eventually open it up to allowing the player to create new custom machines that operate off of scripts written entirely by the player.

It'd lean heavily towards one of those "simulator" games (the setting I have put forth reminds me a bit of car mechanic simulator but with software), but hey, plenty of people enjoy those (myself included).

Another idea: Programming robots for robot fights in your back yard. That would be more action-y and if accompanied with a 3-D editor allowing the player to create custom robots with articulating parts, could have a lot of potential if done right. Coding the bot to properly respond to its array of sensors and inputs from a controller would be a challenging problem for the player, but also very rewarding when you crush the opponent's robot. Would actually be really fun if it was a multiplayer game. Of course, you'd have to create the fighting portion of the game, simulate the robots as well as the damage they receive (which could be as simple as having a health bar or simple value (x/100) for each part), including sensor blackouts (getting a camera knocked out would likely impede the bot's pathfinding), but the more I think about it, the more I want to throw my wallet at whoever decides to make it.

I won't pretend to know how complex making a game like that would be, and I could never hope to create even a small portion of what I described here, but I still wish it existed.', 'This is soooooooooo friggin awesome dude!!!', 'The problem with coding games is that most people will interpret it as a "learning to code" game which kills the fun in the long run.', 'This is the smartest idea I have seen from a game!', 'NAW WE PLAYED SPIRIT ROVER IN MY GAME DESIGN CLASS IN SEPTEMBER', 'Making a coding game?', 'Even if you make it too dificult there are people out there that will still enjoy it', 'Cooool...', 'I beg you to publish this game on Itch and continue working on it.']

['Pls do it on a voxel map', 'The start of a beautiful three years adventure', 'Just FYI if anyone attempts to implement this. The paper calculates the height difference as: 
hDiff=hNew-hOld
It is based on a blogpost at ranmantaru games. In that blogpost however hDiff is calculated as:
hDiff=hOld-hNew
The sign is flipped!!! 
The paper still uses the speed formula from the blogpost without considering this: 
speed = Sqrt(speed^2 + hDiff * gravity)
Guess what happens with a square root with a negative number inside: 
speed = double.NaN
Not only that, but the speed is actually reversed (downhill = slower, uphil = faster).
This error happens when the speed is getting low and hDiff*gravity is larger than speed^2. In the blogpost, the hDiff is also reduced by the amount of eroded/filled sediment before the speed calculation, which is not mentioned in the paper. Probably nobody noticed this because the amount of iterations is limited so that the speed never gets that low to trigger the error ... except when you increase the droplet lifetime to 100 like me üòÑ.', 'i have watched this video tens of times and i still love it', "I had some problems understanding the paper you linked to; if you would please help with that. In the part where he says that when Hdif is positive, the drop drops the sediment until it fits the pit, do I have to program that, or is it already accounted for by the drop's speed going down and if not, is the sediment dropped just the height difference? Secondly, in the part where he says that when the drop deposited sediment, the residue is distributed along the four grid points surrounding it, what does that actually look like as an equation? Thanks.", 'I had some problems understanding the paper you linked to, in the part where he says that the grid point s loose sediment according to their weight values, then he says that the weight values are multiplied by the erosion factor, then he does not mention that it should be also multiplied by the amount of sediment the drop should take which I assumed. could you please explain that to me.', 'Another factor which effects how rocks erode which other commenters haven't mentioned is (an)isotropy. Rocks typically form with a non-uniform fracture orientation based on the stress environment during the formation of those fractures. So rocks in a certain mountain range might be more likely to fracture along non-uniformly oriented planes. I don't know the coding side of it, but I think something in that direction could add a certain "naturalness" to the appearance of the landscape.', "I know you've kinda moved on into things that inspire and interest your mekon-like brain ... but I would love to see your take on tectonic influence.", '4:27 can some one tell me what the shader name i want to make it in unreal engine', 'seems perfect for generating where rivesr/lakes should be.']

['thank you so much, i am making a space exploration game and it wouldent have been able to continue devolopment if it werent for you', 'To solve the vector2 issue in the 2022 version of unity:
list it as a float, with the same name, and then youre going to lose the colors on top of your mountains, to fix that,
 add a clamp node just before the floor node with Min = 0, Max =1 in Shader Graph.', "Thank you for this guide. The amount of aha effects how you use unity to achieve your goal is mind boggling. This series is even helpful for people who don't need the specific solution of procedural planets but who want to get a better workflow with unity.", 'A bit late to the party, but does the biome assigning not work correctly for more than three biomes, or did I miss something in the video? In my case, when I add more biomes, colors from some biomes leak to neighboring biomes. 

Why? When choosing biome, we assign uv.x based on colorGenerator.BiomePercentFromPoint(). Imagine we have five biomes. Then this function will return 0, 0.25, 0.5, 0.75, or 1 based on the biome (without biome mixing). But these values do not correspond to the "biome rows" in the texture. These rows have y values 0.1, 0.3, 0.5, 0.7 and 0.9. As some values are shifted, and we interpolate between texel values, we get color leaks from other biomes. 

Solution: We want values stored in uv.x to match row values in the texture. We can simply remap values from interval [0, 1] to [first row, last row]. One texel in the texture has height of 1 / numberOfBiomes. Therefore first row of texels will have y value of (1 / numberOfBiomes) / 2 = 0.5f / numberOfBiomes. Last row will have y value 1 - (0.5f / numberOfBiomes). We can then map [0, 1] -> [first row, last row] using Mathf.Lerp(0.5f / numberOfBiomes, 1 - (0.5f / numberOfBiomes), biomePercent).', 'To fix the blue planet: add a clamp to the top multiply (connected to one minus and lerp), input from multiply, min 0, max 1, output to the "add" component.', 'For those of you struggling to create a second planet, do this on Planet.cs:
change:
meshFilters[i].GetComponent<MeshRenderer>().sharedMaterial = colourSettings.planetMaterial;
to:
meshFilters[i].GetComponent<MeshRenderer>().sharedMaterial = new Material(colourSettings.planetMaterial);

By default the program uses the static material in the project (one planet will change the parameters which are applied to the 2nd planet)', 'That was awesome. Got some really cool looking planets and managed to learn loads in the process. Thanks for the great series.', 'You need to come back to this and add to it plz! its such a good series', 'How can i give a planet a collider so a character can walk on it?', 'Love the tutorial! Good explanation on how you did everything. I may have missed something however, It was working fine during the beginning but now I am experiencing a problem where the colors disappear whenever I Save my project, Play, or switch Scenes. It keeps the depth, like the mountains and continents, it just takes away the color and I am left with a gray planet. the colors are restored whenever I hit the "Generate Planet" button, but then quickly goes away when I test out my scene or build the game.

Is there something I missed? Or anything that I could try to fix it?']

['Making Shape Keys for the arms didn't work out for me, so will probably have to skip straight to the Integration part with the complete model. When scaled down, the arms became completely separated from the torso.
