HOWEVER, this screws up the whole armature and animations meaning, if you are like me, you have to go back all the way to Part 2...', 'I cant figure out how to color in 2.9+ lol', 'One of the greatest youtubers of all time', 'Wow!  You do things calmly and extraordinary.', 'Cool video, however, I do feel that you are going to end up having a fair bit of mesh bleed to correct for when adding other animations to the character, more so the more extreme skeletal movement your animations imply, say with a strenous climbing animation, or the like. If you have two (or more) animations to work with, the iterative model of simply correcting the bleeds where and as you see them becomes unwieldy, as corrections to fix one animation can break another. If you have loads of animations, that problem scales very poorly.

I suppose the shape keys to shrink the character mesh selectively can work, but, if we're doing selective "culling" anyway: Why not establish a model where the character is actually culled entirely where appropriate?

I think textured clothes, along with more selective 3d-meshes to add brims and such to them, would be more workable, at least for e.g. a computer game or the like.

Love your videos! Lots of great work.', 'Shift+D to duplicate and then P to seperate actually shifts my new "pants" out of alignment with the models legs....?', '13:26', 'So many Fallout4 PA flashbacks =)', "Since people are still clicking in on this, and i apologize if this is mentioned in the video if I haven't gotten to it yet, but you can also transfer the weight painting from one mesh to another and it'll almost perfectly match up, instead of this manual tweaking he shows. ['The explanation makes these so easy to understand, thank you!', 'excelent, thx', "You programmed this fucking circle in Unity, didn't you?", 'A little late to the party, but wanted to point out something that I didn't see in the comments and I don't believe was mentioned in the video: there's a difference between the two ways of implementing the rotation ("90 - " method and swapping x and z).

If you use the "90 - " method (the first one you showed), whenever we give no input, Atan2 is going to become zero (as it should, since the inputDir will just be a Vector3 filled with zeros). However, because we have that constant 90 degrees subtracting from Atan2 * Rad2Deg, the input angle becomes 90 degrees. This means that when we are not pressing anything, our character will face sideways, rotated about the y-axis by 90 degrees.

This doesn't happen when we swap the z and x in the Atan2 function because the constant 90 degrees is not there anymore. In this case, when Atan2 goes to zero (whenever we give no input), the entire inputAngle variable becomes zero, as it should, meaning our character will face forward (+Z) with no input instead of sideways (+X) as it did in the "90 - " method.

I think this explanation is right? Please correct me if I'm wrong.', 'damn you make this too easy bro u should become a math teacher if it were good paying cough cough', 'Are the tooltips about all the methods and parameters you use a monodevelop feature? How can I get those to show up in visual studio? It would help me learn so much üòÖ', 'As some who studied a lot of high-level math, I find the unity coordinate system is very annoying', "I don't need to watch a Sebastian's video till the end to give a Like. Before watching I've already given.", "And here I thought I would never use Trigonometry after I graduate.... 13 years later, I'm brushing up on Trig for my game development career. I've come full four quadrants.", 'Easier chart to learn greater than school üåù']

['<3', 'The problem I have is knowing how unity declares it as struct or class. Transform could be used as a struct more than a class for me at least but its a class in unity. I think C++ pointers make it more clear in terms of whats being referenced and whats being copied', "Your each and every word is golden in this video!. Couldn't be explained any better than this.", 'Cheers', 'Well Explained, fully understand it, thank you so much!', 'Faz apenas 3 dias que estou assistindo esse cara e j√° quero assinar o patreon dele, mds, que homem', 'this is free btw', '"Introduction" to Game Development', "This is why I really wish more high-level languages did references under the same sort of semantics and syntax as pointers in C. 

The problem with making reference semantics so implicit is the fact it's so stupidly easy to introduce bugs into code because the language is all too happy to make things a reference and not tell the programmer. 

In my opinion a well-designed language will always default to values and never ever implicitly switch to reference semantics without the programmer explicitly invoking them. 

This is why C succeeds in so many places C# fails. 

For example, in C# you can do Point p = new Point(5, 10); and C# will do it without complaint. 

In C++, you'd get an error because you're trying to instantiate an object on the heap and then assign its address to something that is NOT a pointer. The compiler would reject the code and tell you this.

It should be Point *p = new Point(5, 10); The * there makes it clear in the code that you're working with a pointer. The programmer EXPLICITLY invokes something like a reference instead of the language sneakily invoking a reference on the programmer behind their back.

Yes, pointers can be confusing, but they're probably the source of a LOT less hard-to-find bugs than implicit references. 

And yes, C++ does actually have a non-pointer reference semantic, but AGAIN, it requires that the programmer explicitly invokes them, and when the actual reference itself is used, the effects fall back to acting like you're acting by value. You pass things by reference into a function in C++, but you're not stuck dereferencing anything to work with it, and when you actually assign from something passed by reference, you're still invoking the expected copy semantics. 

It does have the side effect of introducing side-effects, though, since passing by reference means you're not working with a copy of an object when you pass it into a function, so if you change the object passed by reference in a function it'll be changed in the caller function as well, which is why in C++ you'll most frequently see references being passed into functions as const, so that the object cannot be changed by the called function. 

But, as much as I like Python and work with it, I'm not a fan of languages that assume it's safe to go into reference semantics without the programmer making that clear on their own. It's weird to me classes and structs are supposed to be the distinguishing factor in C#.", '7 minutes passed so quick']

['Hello! There've been some criticisms about the shake looking a bit "off", mostly due to the camera not slowing down towards the end. I have added an update to the source code (available on github from the description) to try and address this. The change is simple: the "speed" variable has been replaced with a maxSpeed and a minSpeed variable. The current speed of the shake is then determined by interpolating between these two values based on the damping curve. (Note that this change does make the "duration" variable less precise, but that shouldn't be too great a concern).

I apologise for not realising that the shake looked a little iffy before recording. Hopefully this update helps!', 'For those who are having problems with the camera moving to (0, 0, 0).

Edit:
Fix for the problem with not being able to flip/mirror pose with CTRL+C and CTRL+SHIFT+V.

Blender 2.78 and 2.79 has a bug with the "Flip Names" feature.
If you remember when Sebastian was naming all the bones, he only named the left side, and then used Flip Names to auto name the right side.
A name like "Foot.L" is supposed to turn into "Foot.R", but thanks to the bug, it instead turns into "Foot.R.001".
This messes up the flip/mirror feature, because they need to have more similar names.
After manually renaming all my bones by removing all the ".001" endings, it now works for me.

Just remember to also rename the vertex groups!
(Object mode > select mesh > edit mode > go to "Data" settings tab to the right > Vertex Groups)', 'How do I determine how man frames I need for my animation?', 'thank you!This is so cool, gonna do it later', 'During the last few frames my arm bones seem to roll, does anyone know why?']

["I've been experiencing some oddities when I started implementing the code. The 'Player' has been bouncing vertically whenever it collides with the platforms and it going through and up walls. Not sure if there is a fix for it. If there is then please let me know.", 'Great tutorials, please make a tutorial for swimming and grab objects.', 'for max slope can climb jump problem, go to Controller2D -> Move() -> and delete if(moveAmount.y != 0)', 'For anybody who gets the error where the player is going up and down a slope for seemingly no reason, I think I found why that happens. When we calculate moveAmount.x, we use Mathf.Abs(moveAmount.y) - hit.distance, assuming that hit.distance ranges from 0 to Mathf.Abs(moveAmount.y) but in reality skinWidth is added to that distance which breaks the formula and essentially gives us negative distance in certain situations, which in turn causes moveAmount.x to change its direction and suddenly we see the player sliding upwards. Additionally, on GitHub Sebastian has changed hit.normal.x in the formula to Mathf.Sign(hit.normal.x) (but has never shown that on YouTube since there is no part 14 of this series). 
In the end, the formula I use for moveAmount.x is: "moveAmount.x = Mathf.Sign(hit.normal.x) * ((Mathf.Abs(moveAmount.y) - hit.distance + skinWidth) / Mathf.Tan(slopeAngle * Mathf.Deg2Rad));"
Still, thank you so much for these tutorials, Sebastian! It's a shame the series has been dropped but what's out is frankly already incredible.', 'did i miss sth? i still can jump up that maxslope :-/', 'ATTENTION: IF YOU ARE HAVING AN MOVEMENT ISSUE WHEN GOING DOWN SLOPES THAT ARE POINT TO THE LEFT.

It took a while, but after a 'few' bugs and issues with the code, i managed to implement your code!", "Hey everyon in the comments, this is an old video but I noticed I was not the only one with this issue.
Several people have mentioned that their endless terrain doesn't generate when moving the viewer in the z axis.

As several other people (Sebatian himself) noted, this may occur is viewerPosition is not set correctly in Update.

It also will happen (like in my case) if in UpdateVisibleChunks in the nested for loop, viewedChunkCoord is not set correctly.

CORECT: Vector2 viewedChunkCoord = new Vector2(currentChunkCoordX + xOffset, currentChunkCoordY + yOffset);
INCORRECT: Vector2 viewedChunkCoord = new Vector2(currentChunkCoordX + xOffset, currentChunkCoordY = yOffset);", 'How can i make this generate only one chunk?', 'Having trouble with scripts not running on your chunks?
Rather than constantly setting the last visible chunks not visible each frame, you can easily make a command checking rather it is our of range and disabling it if it is out of range.

Because the chunks are constantly being SetActive(false) and then true again, the scripts never get to run their update functions (if the script is on the generated chunk). So by using this other method here, you avoid that.']

I don't think you read your new comments or anything. but here goes. I have created a procedural generator for a vehicle, and that generator has a smoothing option built in, where I determine the distance between existing vertices in a mesh and compare that to the list of vertices in the list, if the distance is less than 0.005 meters, the system uses that vertice index to create the triangle. I do this in sets of three or 4 cause i need both triangles and quads. thing is, when running the smoothing code, the uvs do not work. I know your generator uses smooth vertices as I did not notice any of the issue related to flat shading showing up in the mesh. your way of doing things allows for uv coordinats to be preserved despite the fact that the mesh is smooth. I can things 1 of two ways. wait for you to help.. or do the irritating thing and analyze your code and compare it to how I am doing things. if anything it might have to do with the fact that I am adding in vertice, not all at once, but slowly as I progress down the entire generation script.... i use an ADDQuad function that takes in 4 points, a bool for auto uvs, and a bool for smoothing, then I pass in vector2s created from a function that converts vertice coords into pixel coords. then I use a uvmapper I made to uv unwrap the generated object. I have the uvs working in flat shaded mode, but in smoothing mode, nothing works.", 'I was going to post here the new smoothing code I created that corrects the problems of the previous version, but I think its too long', 'why when i create new materials / save the project the plane becomes white and i have to re-generate to get the generate plane with noise / colour / mesh?', 'I never really grasped meshes, even after your tutorials, until today. I made a voxel based model creator and plan on expanding it to include shapes other than cubes. I had a hard time until I managed to create my first cube with 6 sides all part of the same mesh. was easier than I thought it would be. I also did something complicated and used a hightmap as limiter for genration 2D horizontal density maps, where the float value is the density of a voxel tile and can determine its materials. wth the hight values being used to prvent the game from placing objects above the surface of the hightmap I created a psuedo marching cube code. but it was too laggy. so I learned to make my own meshes with handcoded vertices!! thanks for all the great tutorials.', 'Well mountains are usually lines(Look at the Carpathian mountains) or high lands. This generator seems to create islands with lonely mountains. What I would do is overlay 4 noise maps: the land map(everything above sea level), the hills map(little hills and depressions), the mountain chain map(contains mountain chains, eg. the Carpathians, the Alps, the Grand Canyon) and the highlands map(contains non chain-like mountains). The land map would be generated with randomly positioned lesser and greater seeds. Lesser seeds would expand to small sizes and come in clusters while greater seeds would expand to much bigger sizes(often times fusing together) and be far apart. Lesser seeds would generate islands and greater seeds would generate continents. The hills map would also be generated with lesser seeds(the spawning location and frequency of would be determined by biomes). The mountain chain map would be built from several starting points. from these 1-3 vectors would spring forth going away from each other. Each step there would be a new greater vector, the direction of which will be allowed to randomly deviate in some range of degrees. This range would be determined by the squiggliness variable and the side preference variable(if the vector prefers going left or right). The side preference would be randomly chosen each step. At the end of each greater vector(length of those vectors is determined by the length and girth variable + chance) the would be a high chance of 1-2 lesser vectors(length determined by girth variable and chance) spawning opposite each other. These lesser vectors would create valleys in between them. Also at each Greater vector end there would be a "radiating" height increase. Lastly the Highlands map would be generated by tightly packed and really girthy, short and squiggly mountain chains. There would also be a high chance that generated lesser vectors would be converted into greater vectors.', 'Is there a way to do this on an actual terrain object and not a plane object so we can use the tree painting tool?', 'for anyone who is wondering why their world is just a black texture disabling the plane should fix this. this happens because if 2 objects are in the same position and the 2 objects have the same look unity just defaults to a black material.', "If you don't see the mesh. Right under scene at the top of the view, where it says shaded. click on that and press Shaded Wireframe."]

It's brilliantly easy to follow and has helped me to understand why, when I followed other tutorials on the subject, things weren't working.", 'Important Things you should know before starting this Tutorial...

1.	There are script changes missing in some of the videos that can cause you headaches. You will need the source code he provides in the notes to compare to your own from time to time.
2.	He breaks the Falloff Map feature at the end when he reorganises all of his scripts.  It no longer affects the terrain mesh.
3.	Everything to do with textures in this tutorial will be useless for a lot of developers, because he hard codes his system to only use the One Shader we create during the lessons. ['the public interface IDamageable gives me a error in LivingEntity,using unity 2020.3.301f', 'for my enemy, i had added 2 cubes to act as hands and put them as children of the base. but when the projectile collided with them, this part (IDamageable damagableObject = hit.collider.GetComponent<IDamageable>();) would always be null, even though they also have the layer Enemy attached. and that made it so my enemies would not die even though the bullets were colliding with the enemy. i removed the rigid body component of the hands, so the bullets just hit the base instead of the hand, and everything seems to be working fine. im just writing this incase someone else is experiencing similar problems.

['In the latest versions of Unity you'll need to add the line "using UnityEngine.AI;" to get access to things like the NavMeshAgent.', "Q: Why use raycasts instead of OnTriggerEnter to detect projectile collisions?

I am trying to use this as a base for my platformer game, and have run into a scenario where I have too many raycasts because almost all objects in the game are moving. What's the best way to deal with this? I thought of querying a n*playerspeed box around the player, then only doing raycasts from moving platforms which intersect that box. The problem naturally is the timing of when the intersection test returns, and in what order the movement should happen. There is also some trouble with being pushed by two moving platforms at the same time, e.g. standing on a horizontally moving platform when a horizontally moving wall comes into contact with you.

thanks for the tutorial. heres hoping you still check these comment sections", 'I am having trouble with the first little bit with the passenger movement struct. My errors say that my variables do not exist in the current context. I have other issues along those lines. Can anyone help me?', 'The dark humor of this is that .transform calls a get component on the backend. But still better than too many.', 'Another thing to note with platforms in this tutorial is that, depending on your platform and player sizes, you may end up falling "between" the vertical raycasts on the platform. Increase the number of vertical raycasts to fill the gaps and you may experience less clipping and strange behaviour in either direction. It helps if you bring the Debug.DrawRay() statement over from the Controller2D into the PlatformController in the vertically moving and horizontally moving FOR loops.', "Some problems I've come across here. It's probably not a good idea to move the passenger downwards when the player is below. What this does is it causes the player to hang at the bottom of the platform if they've jumped into it which is totally unnatural for a platformer. Since the player is never really otherwise pushed down (the platform moves down through the player if the player is grounded), the use of downward raycasts is redundant. It's best to only check vertical movement when the platform is moving up and let the last check of passenger riding on top to take care of downwards movement. One other significant and complicated problem, if you decide you want one way moving platforms, the detection for moving the player horizontal or down when they are stood on top of the platform does not detect when the player is actually on top of the platform which means you'll get get strange behavior of the player being sucked into the platform and pushed up if you try to jump through the platform. Implementing any check to make sure the player AABB is above the platform AABB unfortunately can interfere with the platforms ability to still hit the player with the raycast and move the player down when the player is riding on top and the platform is moving downwards, so you get a constant issue of the player bouncing and not staying attached to the platform. Yep, this is proving challenging to work out! ü§î", 'I respect you. With your tutorial, I can see such a clean programming. It is multiple level ahead, but I can learn and make reference out of it.']

["This is awesome! I've always been interested in procedural generation, and I like the way you explain things!", 'Late comment. Im not quite sure about this but i think there is still a problem with that break in the loop.
Assume we do have 4 Rooms A,B, C and D. A is nearest to C (A->C), B -> D, C -> D and D -> B.
We start iterating at A. A will connect with C.          A<->C
We now look at roomA = B and it connects with D. B<->D.
Now we look at roomA = C. The loop breaks because C is already connected with roomB = A. But C should have been connected to D.
Now we look at roomA = D. The loop breaks which is okay because D -> B and they are already connected.
The map now looks the following: A <-> C, B <-> D. The connection between C and D is missing and we have 2 disjoint caves. Instead if C correctly connected to D there would also be in addition just 1 continuous cave.
However, if the loop just continues with the next room instead of breaking, there might occur another problem, namely that the already connected room (that was skipped) might have been the closest one and then a connection is made with the 2nd closest room. So it is necessary to check the distance of the already connected room too. Then afterwards, before creating the passage, check in addition if the best rooms are already connected and only create the passage when they are not. Or simply connect them again, if this does not break the code of the next episodes.', '—è –º–µ–ª–∫–∏–π –ø–æ–º–Ω—é –∫–æ–≥–¥–∞-—Ç–æ —Ç–æ–∂–µ –¥–µ–ª–∞–ª —Ç–∞–∫—É—é —Ñ–∏–≥–Ω—é (–Ω–∞ Delphi) + —Ç–∞–º –ø–æ–∏—Å–∫ –∫—Ä–∞—Ç—á–∞–π—à–µ–≥–æ –ø—É—Ç–∏, –ø–æ–ª—É—á–∏–ª–æ—Å—å –ø—Ä–∏–º–µ—Ä–Ω–æ —Ç–æ–∂–µ —Å–∞–º–æ–µ)', 'Why use Cord instead of something like a vector2 ?', "I don't know what's happening with mine, but the amount of time it takes to generate since this video in the series is insanely high. Can I implement a high score feature in the last two hours of this game jam...', 'Hi guys, As of now in 2021 dreamlo still works in pc and on android with android version 8 and lower and with devices greater than android version 8(9,10 and so on) they need ssl to work which you can get by donating 5 dollars to dreamlo maker, I have to now use other leaderboard so thought to tell everyone about the problem.', 'how do I replace WWW with unitywebrequest?', "U R MY HERO I SEARCHED 99999999999999999999 CHANNELS Vƒ∞DEOS FORMS BUT I COULDN'T Fƒ∞ND A DATA BASE Lƒ∞KE THƒ∞S GOD BLESS U", "*DO NOT USE THIS*

I know I'm a little late to the party, but seriously, this solution is extremely insecure. For starters, the connection is not encrypted, it uses standard HTTP 1.1, meaning it is extrmely easy for someone to retreive the private code simply by sniffing their network traffic while playing the game (software like Wireshark makes this trivial). Since the packets are not encrypted, it will expose the private code. THIS GIVES AN ATTACKER COMPLETE CONTROL OF THE LEADERBOARD. Even then, the secret code gets stored in the local binary, meaning anyone could reverse the binary to retreive it. Hard-coding secrets into locally running code is generally never a good idea.

A solution would be to use a scoreboard wherein the communication to the sever is encrypted, and there are server-side checks in place to verify that the new score is legitimate (for example, if it's a puzzle game, submit the solutions to the server for varification). Furthermore, the credentials provided to update a score should NOT be usable to manipulate the scoreboard in other ways, and a unique token should be generated for each player which only allows them to update their own scores and name. Of course, there will still be game hacking that could mess with the scores, but this should at least make the scoreboard itself secure from direct attacks.", 'Thanks for source code', 'www obstole', 'Excellent tutorial!
Thanks']

['The five letters are not random.  English is a language.  Five letter (non plural) words usually are a single sylable, occasionally double.  Every sylable has at least one vowel and there are only six of them.  Words that have a single vowel are very likely to have r,l&n either directly before or after the vowel.  The same applies less strongly for two vowels.  (Linguists do not consider r,l,n constants unless they are at the beginning of the word; m&w, too.)    Then there are common double consonants, such as ch,th,sh,sc,st,sp,sq(u),sk which can appear either before or after the vowel(s). \nThese patterns greatly reduce the possible combinations of five letters.  I would bet my bottom dollar that if the computer were taught these patterns its score would improve considerably.  I, with my limited vocabulary, lost five of my first 100 games and, since applying these insights, have lost none of my second 100.  SALET or SLATE are bad starting words.  I have been using ARIEL to great effect.', 'Great video. Is it possible that practically,  many resrarchers simply ingnore the very existance of the  falls  +/- ?', 'The way I think about it, the Base Rate Fallacy happens because we forget to consider the base rate. Sensitivity and specificity are expressed as proportions, in the same realm as probabilities. So it's easy to point at the 90% accuracy and say "that's your probability". By using odds ratios, you force yourself to take another step to reach the answer: take the base rate into account.

You included the parity bits in your count. Was that a mistake on your part, or am I wrong?\nEDIT2: Hmmm.... There's one thing I didn't consider. For a simple example of the union of sets of position with even numbers of positions with ones in them not having an even number of positions of ones in them, imagine two sets, each of which contain for one-slots, three of which are shared between the two sets, so that the union of the two sets has 5 one-slots.", 'you deserve a nobel in teaching', '14:25 I did not understand this part..can someone explain please???', "We don't deserve this knowledge condensed to such a simple form. ['There are many questions around contact tracing apps, and I'll try to address some of them in this pinned comment.  What's presented is, in essence, the DP-3T algorithm, but needless to say it's a much-simplified version, so most security-related questions can be answered by going to https://github.com/DP-3T and reading the full details.  For example, if you're thinking that when Bob's phone recognizes some signals in the hospital's database, it can deduce _when_ Bob met with the someone now known to be sick by looking at where that message shows up on its "What I heard" list, you may be interested to learn how the full details of how these ids are generated and uploaded don't quite make that as possible as it would be for the simplified version outlined in Nicky's post.

One of the biggest concerns is over the efficacy of Bluetooth systems like this.  For example, false positives due to signals shared through apartment walls, and false negatives due to touching a shared surface without ever being near someone.  No one claims that these will catch all contacts, but the goal is to have a system more scalable than in-person interviews, and what you need is for R to stay consistently below 1, not to catch all cases.  Any serious plans for reopening including a system like this also would include other practices driving this reproductive number down, like mask-wearing and distancing where possible.  Also, to the accuracy concerns, it seems worth mentioning that at least one person I know is working on https://www.novid.org/ which incorporates ultrasound to get a better sense of proximity.

Many government-issued contact-tracing apps *do* use GPS in some way, so you'd want to stay informed about whatever specific system is being advertised to you.  The purpose of Nicky's post is to make clear that contact tracing does not _imply_ location tracking.  If people (or governments) really want to use GPS based contact tracing too, there's no reason you can't have both.  But if you're in a country where people can choose to opt-in, you won't be including people who are concerned about privacy. 

As to the status of the Google/Apple system, the first phase of their plan involved putting out an API that developers can use to build apps according to these standards, which is now done.  The second phase will involve doing something built into the phone's OS, which people can opt in to. ['Summary of the confusion on problem 2.  TL;DR, given the spirit of the question it should have also specified that f(x) > 0 for all x, and I'm clearly prone to deep confusion while trying to juggle the many balls of live broadcasting.


The question asks about a function f satisfying f(a + b) = f(a)f(b).  The relevant part of the question was whether f(-1) must be 1 / f(1).


- It was originally graded in a way to suggest that this _does_ indeed need to be true.
- While "explaining" it, I realized that the explanation required that f(0) = 1, and questioned whether this is necessarily true.  I even said, "oh, you could just scale it".  This thought of scaling is not correct, since (c*f(a))(c*f(b)) = c^2 f(a + b), so the lhs and rhs doesn't scale the same way.
- At 27:48, Sam points out that the constant function f(x) = 0 doesn't work, which I misread as asking about whether f(x) = 0 for some x (sorry Sam!).
- Crispin points out that f(0) must be 1 because f(x) = f(x + 0) = f(x)*f(0).  This is true, as long as f(x) does not equal 0 everywhere, but at that point, I was still weirdly blind to that edge case and enthusiastically accepted this as a reason that the question was originally graded correctly.
- At 49:07, more of the discussion that has been happening on twitter is brought to screen, where Eric correctly points out that Crispin's proof doesn't work for the constant function f(x) = 0, which  Sam had said all along much earlier and I misread.

The line swaps between two pivots.  It sweeps out a region and will return to the original pivot once it has completed a half rotation in the plane of interaction.  Since any three points are mutually offset, there is only ever one point in the exact same interaction plane as the interacting point along the lines of the pivot exchange.


There are only two configurations therefore that are stable that preclude other interactions.

1.  An oscillation on the outer boundaries between two or less points.
2.  A cyclic oscillation around a point OR points in the domain: ie a lattice

2 is trivial to disprove because there aren't any configurations possible due to mutual offsetting.  Since the only configuration in which points can be avoided infinitely are those which induce cyclic motion that preclude it, means you only need to prove 1 - that there exists no configurations between which the pivot doesn't switch.


Since the sweep is predictable, that sweep takes in the entire search space.  The pivot also does not change the plane of the line - it continues as it would normally.  If it were chaotic it would not be possible to prove because there would exist an insignificant probabilistic chance of a mutually sweeping pivot between a small group of objects.  Thus provided that there is a point between that point and the last, there will always be another in network point to look at and the only case in which this is not true involves sweeping area outside of S, which is irrelevent.

So, for two bodies - it is impossible for the interaction space before to have contained another point since the interaction wouldn't have occured.  If another body exists, it therefore HAS to exist in the post interaction space and since that frame will sweep exactly one full half turn until it returns, all intractable points will be contained in that region.

Therefore, if another body exists, it will always be interacted with and the only configuration in which that does not happen involves conditions rendered impossible by the lack of triplet co-linearity.  If three bodies can't be in a configuration to avoid mutual oscillation, adding additional bodies requires that it is possible to exclude all other bodies from the post swap event space.  Since this is not possible - the only rotations precluded are those which have already been covered clockwise down the interaction plane and would have resulted in an interaction anyway - all bodies are inevitably swept up, eventually.", 'On the "social" point, I've noticed this phenomenon in all sorts of things I've taught to people: programming, dance, woodworking, video games, etc. For human beings, it seems like an essential part of learning something is forgetting what it was like not to know that thing.', 'So I pasted this question into ChatGPT version 4 (the newest one since March 1), and this is what is says:
1. Let S be a finite set of at least two points in the plane, and let n be the number of points in S. Since no three points are collinear, any line through two points of S will determine a unique angle with the horizontal axis.

2. Consider all pairs of points (A, B) in S, and for each pair, calculate the angle that the line AB makes with the horizontal axis. Let's call this angle Œ∏(AB). Since there are n points, there are n(n-1)/2 pairs of points, and thus n(n-1)/2 angles. Divide the range of angles from 0 to 180 degrees into n-1 equally-sized intervals.

3. By the Pigeonhole Principle, there must be at least one interval that contains at least n angles Œ∏(AB). Pick one such interval and let's call it I.

4. Now, let's choose a line l, such that it forms an angle Œ± with the horizontal axis, where Œ± is the midpoint of interval I. Choose an arbitrary point P in S as the starting pivot.

5. When the windmill process starts, since the line l initially makes an angle within the interval I, the next point Q it encounters will also form an angle within I, as the line rotates clockwise about P. When the line pivots about Q, the same argument applies, and the line will continue to rotate and pivot about points in S that form angles within I.

6. Observe that the windmill process will eventually use each point in S as a pivot at least once. Since there are at least n angles within I and n points in S, we know that there will always be a point in S that the line can pivot to after rotating clockwise.

7. The windmill process will continue indefinitely, and each point in S will be used as a pivot infinitely many times. This is because the line will keep rotating and meeting points with angles within the interval I, and since there are at least n angles in I, the line will never "run out" of points to pivot to.

Fascinating how ChatGPT can answer this question, but do you all see what step is inaccurate?', 'Looks like we got 4.3 million aspiring mathematicians', 'after watching your videos for a year, i‚Äôm baffled at how you consistently explain not only the solution to a math problem, but the process of thinking for an entire topic within math. Props', '2 plus 2 is 4. minus 1 thats 3 quickmaths', 'WOW THIS IS AMAZING', 'Intuitively I expect the answer to be yes. Prove it? Not this dude', 'I kind of feel that I wasted 16 min of my life']

['Some added notes (I may come back to add more later):

1) There's a slight error in the video where I say the answer is floor(pi/theta).  Really it should be ceil(pi/theta) - 1, to account for the cases where pi/theta is an integer.  For example, when the mass ratio is 1, theta will be pi/4, so pi/theta is 4, but there are 3 clacks.  As stated in the video, though, you still think about this is "how many times can you add theta to itself before it surpasses (or equals) pi?"


2) What I animate here as I say "angle of reflection" and "angle of incidence" differs a little with convention.  Typically in optics, you look at the angle between the beam and a line *perpendicular* to the mirror, rather than with the mirror itself.

3) Some people have asked about if the tan(x) ‚âà x approximation, being off by only a cubic error term, is actually close enough not to affect the final count.  It's actually a very interesting answer!  I really went back and forth on whether or not to include this in the video but decided to leave it out to better keep things to the point.  This difference between arctan(x) and x could be problematic for our final count if, at some point when you're looking at the first 2n digits of pi, the last n of them are all 9's.  It seems exceedingly unlikely that this should be true.  For example, among the first 100 million digits of pi, the maximal sequence of consecutive 9's has length 8, whereas you'd need a sequence of 50 million for things to break our count!  Nevertheless, this is quite difficult to prove, related to the question of whether or not pi is a "normal" number, roughly meaning that it's digits behave like a random sequence.  It was left as a conjecture in Galperin's paper on the topic.  See sections 9 and 10 of that paper (linked in the description) for more details.

4) A word on terminology:  I tend to use the word ‚Äúphase space‚Äù to describe any space like the ones described in this video and the last, encoding some state of some system.  This is common in the context of math, but you should know, that often in the context of mechanics, this term is reserved for the special case of a space which encodes both the positions and the momenta of all the objects involved.  For example, in that setting, the ‚Äúphase space‚Äù here would be four-dimensional, where the four coordinates represent the position and momentum of each pair of blocks.  The term ‚Äúconfiguration space‚Äù, in contrast, just refers to one where the coordinates describe the positions of all the objects involved, which is what we did here.

I hope you enjoyed this little sequence.  I still get happy whenever I think about the phenomenon and the various explanations for it.', 'œÄ', '–¢—É–ø–æ–π?', 'I would like to ask.. Then the upper bound of the inertial subrange is about 1/6 L, and the lower bound is about 60 L (œÅUL/¬µ)^(-3/4), where œÅ is the density of the fluid, U is the mean velocity over the plate, and ¬µ is the flow viscosity. Altogether Re = œÅUL/¬µ is the Reynolds number.\nWhat defines this range, is that the kinetic energy only cascades down, but it isn't produced (like at bigger scales) neither dissipated (like at smaller scales).", "6:15 I think one important observation regarding incompressible flow, is that yes, indeed air is compressible, but so is liquid water, and all fluids for that matter (in fact a little bit of compressibility is what allows the concept of pressure). For many applications, with no pressure gradients (like in external flow, like the one shown in the footage) and with speeds well below the speed of sound (definitely like shown in the footage), compressibility effects are quite negligible. The average will naturally split the probability space, since if it's smaller (let's say at 30deg then the 30 deg pie is of course smaller than a 160 deg pie, so we can say the line with the average should also be perpendicular to the first line (for a circle, assuming as here constant prob). Casually this becomes X and Y, and the probability of the 3rd point is the opposite quadrant as shown in the video.\nLet's continue similarly for the 3D. Let's try to find the average placement of 3 lines in 3D. Again as before, we fix the first one let's say in the X axis (in 3D now though). To obtain the next one, we need a perpendicular one, of which there are infinite (around the plane YZ), so let's just pick the Y axis, since all the lines in this plane should have the same chance. Then for the 3rd point, there's a line that can be picked at random that is the furthest (perpendicular) from the other 2, which is the Z axis. Now assuming the 3 points in the 3 main axis: X=1,Y=0,Z=0; X=0,Y=1,Z=0; X=0,Y=0,Z=1, we can see how only in the opposite quadrant would the tetrahedron make the point be in the middle. That means on average there's 1 quadrant, out of the 8 of a sphere, that on average gives us the center contained within. 1 out of 8, 1/8th. ['A guaranteed way to generated these triples is to take an odd number, square it, divide it in half, and add/subtract .5. The odd number,  half of the square minus .5, and half of the square plus .5 will be your triple', 'The graph looks like multiplying x with i on a graphic calculator xD', 'Me: wonders about a concept on my own.
You: always have a video explaining it eloquently and comprehensively. TY!', 'The Pythagorean triple for (46, 45) is (91,4140, 4141).
The first term 91 is also the sum of 46+45. 
4141 is the product of the 13th prime number (41) times the 26th prime number (101). 
Note that the 3rd term is the 2nd term +1.
You probably see that 45 and 46 are the numbers of the X,Y chromosomes in Human DNA. 
But did you see that 41 is the number of Jesus in the genealogy from Abraham to Christ (Matthew 1:1). 
And 91 = 7x13, two divine prime numbers ( completion 7, priesthood 13).', 'Could this be used on a gigantic scale to find a perfect Euler brick?', "You can see more viscerally how complex multiplication works by using Euler's identity, r*e^theta*i", 'Here is a cool trick.
Take any number (easier with odd numbers)
Square it, divide by 2 and and subtract 1/2 to each half. And there you go a special right triangle.

For example:
{3} --> ()¬≤ --> 9 --> /2 --> 4.5 --> +-0.5 --> {4,5}
Result: 3, 4, 5

You can use it backwards to see if this is the minimal version of triangle.

For example: in 3,4,5 the difference between 4 and 5 is 1.
Same for 7,24,25.
Those are the base version of the triangles.

So if we have something like: 6,8,10
Then take the difference of the 2 big numbers and that might be the ratio of the original triangle.
Possible ratio: 10-8=2

Take 6 and process it through our method. And divide by ratio.
6¬≤-->36-->/2(ratio)-->18
If the 2 other sides of the triangle add up to the result. Which in this case 10+8 is indeed 18.

Than our ratio is correct and to find our original triangle we can divide by that ratio.
6,8,10 / 2 = 3,4,5.

9,12,15 for ex
Possible ratio: 15-12=3
9¬≤=81 --> 81/3 = 27 , 15+12 is indeed 27.
Ratio is confirmed to be 3.
9,12,15 / 3 = 3,4,5', 'Them: "I hate maths it's such a boring subject"
Meanwhile maths: 10:12', '3blue.1brown41592653589793', 'Im 3 years late, but I made a python script to generate pythagorean triplets! (Exact same method shown in video)

print("Pythagorean Triplet Generator")
u, v, = int(input("Input any random positive integer: ")), int(input("Input any random positive integer: "))
assert v > 0 and u > 0
u, v = min(u, v), max(u, v)

print("Pythagorean Triplet Generated!")
first_num = v**2 - u**2
second_num = 2 * v * u
third_num = v**2 + u**2
print(f"{first_num}¬≤ + {second_num}¬≤ = {third_num}¬≤")

:D it works perfectly, in fact its weirdly fun just generating triplets like this']

['Next up is integrals.   Follow the full playlist at http://3b1b.co/calculus

By the way, there is a piece of math, commonly called "non-standard analysis", which makes infinitesimals a rigorous notion, thereby avoiding the need to use limits.  That is, in the real number system something like 0.000....(infinitely many 0's)...1 doesn't make sense, it's not an actual number.  But the "hyperreal numbers" of non-standard analysis are constructed so as to include a number like this.

I have no problem with that system.  I think it's great to invent new math and new number systems meant to rigorously capture a useful intuitive notion, although the construction of the hyperreal numbers requires some questionable usage of the axiom of choice.  But I do think it's important to first learn about limits, and how mathematicians made sense out of calculus using the standard real number line without resorting to infinitesimals.  It's not a matter of clinging to old systems, it's because limits help to gain a deeper appreciation for structure and character of the real numbers themselves, which in turn will help to understand any extension of those numbers.', "I think there is a error at 6', I got the idea, but to match the equation with the graphic, you need to place the empty dot at x=2, not at zero. // For 5 disks, a is the smallest, e is the largest, and the positions they move to in order

a2 b1 a1 c2
a3 b2 a2 e3

a2 b1 a1 d3
a3 b2 a2 c3

b_total_moves = 2^ring_count-2

while(c_pos <= 31)

    move_list += a_pos

while(d_pos <= 31)
    d_pos += 2^ring_count-1
    move_list += a_pos

while(e_pos <= 31)
    e_pos += 2^ring_count
    move_list += a_pos

The statement "The Basis of a vector space is a set of linearly independent vectors that span the entire space" is a fundamental concept in linear algebra.

To understand it better, let's consider an example.

Suppose we have a two-dimensional vector space, V, which contains all possible linear combinations of two vectors u and v. That is, any vector in V can be expressed as a linear combination of u and v.

Now, let's say that u = (1, 0) and v = (0, 1) are the two vectors in V. We can verify that any vector in V can indeed be expressed as a linear combination of u and v. For example, the vector (2, 3) can be written as:

(2, 3) = 2(1, 0) + 3(0, 1)

This means that (1, 0) and (0, 1) span the entire vector space V.

However, we still need to show that these two vectors are linearly independent. This means that neither vector can be expressed as a linear combination of the other. In other words, there is no non-zero scalar values a and b such that:

a(1, 0) + b(0, 1) = (0, 0)

We can easily see that this is true, since the only solution to this equation is a = b = 0. Therefore, (1, 0) and (0, 1) are linearly independent.

Since (1, 0) and (0, 1) are both linearly independent and span the entire space V, they form a basis for V.

In summary, the basis of a vector space is a set of linearly independent vectors that span the entire space. The concept of a basis is important because any vector in the space can be uniquely represented as a linear combination of the basis vectors, and this representation can be used to solve many problems in linear algebra.', "There is another very good way of thinking about an independent vector. It's as follows :-
If a vector has some non - zero component in a direction which is perpendicular to the direction of all other vectors, it is linearly independent from the system of those vectors as it can't be expressed as a linear combination of other vectors in any way.", 'so good', 'The idea of the moving plane, or line in 2 dimensional space, makes for a wonderful mental image when explaining why the entire set of the space becomes reachable even when vectors deviate only minutely in general direction.', 'cant thank you enough.', 'what', 'SIR, AMAZING LINEAR ALGEBRA BASICS VIDEOS.']

Las antropologias', 'I believe the definition of a vector from a CS perspective in this video is a little off. A two-dimensional vector in computer science is not a vector of length two, but instead a vector in which each index only contains one object or primitive type. A three dimensional vector would be a vector in which each element is a two dimensional vector, and that pattern repeats.', 'This is a really great playlist!', 'nobel prize', 'i use vectors for ray tracing.', 'Thanks!', 'BASED', 'You weren't really fair to computer scientists.

In the CS realm, a vector is an ordered sequence of any length where every element has the same type. The fact that each element has the same type is much more important than the length of the vector. Dollars and square feet may both be numbers, but any half-way decent programmer will tell you that A) they're not the same type, and B) if you neglect to structure your code so that the compiler understands they're not the same type and keeps you from confusing them, you'll eventually be sorry.

A data structure containing an ordered collection of elements that can be of different types, where the length is part of the data type (that is, a structure of a different length is a different type) is a tuple, not a vector.

Your example of a price and an area is either a tuple (if the programming language supports it) or a class/struct/object. If I were to review a piece of code that used a vector for data like that, I'd reject the code until the programmer used the right data structure, specifically because of the "eventually be sorry" part above.']
